#: 303R10
msgid "Schloss Pickas, Free City of Danzig, January 19, 1935. Dear Mr. Ripley, in the province of Xian in China is a little-known monument that ranks among the wonders of the world. You may be interested in it as a subject for your amusing newspaper feature, which appears even here in our little city-state, perched between Germany and Poland. I speak of the tomb of Qin Xie Huangdi, the man who united China for the first time and reigned as emperor some 2300 years ago. For his eternal resting place, he had a great chamber excavated and covered with a copper dome, representing the heavens. Inside he built a veritable miniature China, complete with temples, palaces and buildings of all sorts, overlooking rivers and even a sea of mercury. Row upon row of terracotta soldiers guard the way to unimaginable treasures, including the emperor's emerald seal, a powerful talisman. The chief architect of the place was a certain sage known as Master Lu. At the emperor's command, Liu had traveled across the seas, searching for an elixir of immortality. And though he failed in his quest, he did bring home much arcane knowledge. Liu devised many cunning traps to ensure that the emperor's tomb would never be plundered. Indeed, to this day, no one has so much as penetrated the great mound of earth, now called Mount Li, that covers the dome. I have devoted many years of study to this remarkable monument, compared with which the great pyramids of Egypt are but clumsy heaps of stone. And lately my efforts have been rewarded. Something has come into my hands that I believe provides the key to the tomb. Alas, my health is failing. I am unable to visit the Liu materials in the Hall of Classics at the Imperial School in Peiping, or mount the necessary expeditions to uncover the few remaining clues to Master Lu's secret. One of the leading authorities on this period in China, a Doctor Twelve Trees, is rumored to be in thieves, but so far I've had no success verifying the rumor. I am writing to you, Mr. Ripley, to ask if you would be willing to undertake a joint venture with me. I will carry the banner of science, and you that of the fantastic. I am certain that nowhere in the works of man will you find anything more worthy of inclusion in your believe-it-or-not feature than the tomb of Xue Huangdi. Respectfully yours, Otto Sixth Baron von Seltzen."
msgstr ""

